        "**Abstract:**\n",
        "The research analyses SIMD data to identify areas of socio-economic deprivation in Scotland, focusing on income, education, and employment SIMD domains. Using QGIS and Python, it highlights disparities across the different domains and regions and discusses how current interventions fall short of addressing the issues and proposes community-based interventions, such as job training and improved transport, to address these issues.\n",

      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "e39442ee-8280-4412-a7dd-934b14c1f04a",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "e39442ee-8280-4412-a7dd-934b14c1f04a"

      "source": [
        "## Introduction\n",
        "Socio-economic disparities are ever present in daily life and politics in Scotland; for example, these are 2 of the top headlines on BBC News Scotland today: “‘The budget seems good on paper—I hope it saves my job.” (Jackson, 2024), “Scottish Budget 2025-26: At a glance” (Cochrane, 2024). Despite government interventions, statistics show that 21% of Scotland’s population lives in relative poverty, while 17% live in absolute poverty.(Scottish Government, 2024). These figures indicate that government policies aimed at reducing poverty, such as welfare programs and subsidies, have not fully addressed the root of the issues like wage stagnation, unemployment, and high living costs. This prevalence of poverty is why targeted interventions, such as community-based and community-led solutions, are needed in both urban areas like Glasgow and Dundee that have various areas facing deprivation and rural areas that are facing deprivation due to their remoteness and limited access to resources. The Scottish Index of Multiple Deprivation (SIMD) (Scottish Government, 2020) provides a framework for understanding these disparities. This research looks at 3 of the domains: income, education, and employment. This research aims to use spatial and statistical analysis of SIMD data to identify priority areas for intervention. The research aims to answer the question of what areas in Scotland are the most deprived. And what are possible solutions for this? To answer this, the research uses a multi-criteria evaluation (MCE) in QGIS, combined with Python for statistical visualisation, to identify and visualise poverty hotspots for intervention.\n",
        "\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "cb383aa0-bded-4d8e-aa3c-c0e80be48d08",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "cb383aa0-bded-4d8e-aa3c-c0e80be48d08"
      },
      "source": [
        "## Methodology\n",
        "Methology\n",
        "\n",
        "Data\n",
        "\n",
        "The research uses SIMD data on income, employment, and education. The data was sourced from the SIMD dataset (Scottish Government, 2020), which provides rankings for different indicators of deprivation from Data Zones across Scotland\n",
        "\n",
        "Software\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "QGIS for conducting the MCE and geospatial processing.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "Python for data cleaning, analysis, and visualisation using libraries such as pandas, geopandas, matplotlib, seaborn, rasterio, and numpy.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "Methods\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "An MCE was conducted in QGIS by combining the deprivation criteria (income, employment, and education) to calculate a suitability index. SIMD rankings for income, education, and employment were normalised for the suitability indexes. All three deprivation factors were weighed equally to avoid bias in the suitability calculations. A residential zone constraint was created using population data that was rasterised to exclude non-residential areas to ensure people live in the areas identified. The factors were combined with the constraint to produce a suitability index. This index was classified into five categories: Very Low to Very High. Then, an index containing only very high values was created.Python was used for statistical analysis and data visualisation.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "Heatmaps for education, employment, and income deprivation were generated using seaborn to visualise spatial variations. A plasma colour map was applied for a clear differentiation of the areas. Raster files of the overall and specific suitability indexes were visualised using matplotlib and rasterio. Non-relevant values were masked.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n"
      ]
    },

        "     plt.imshow(data,cmap='plasma')\n"

    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "Results\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "The suitability index combines domain rankings of income, education, and employment to identify areas most in need of intervention. Darker regions on the map indicate areas with the highest levels of deprivation across all domains and thus more suitable.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "Key Findings\n",
        "\n",
        "Hotspots: Urban areas such as Glasgow and Dundee consistently appear as the most deprived, with high levels of need across all domains.\n",
        "\n",
        "Rural Deprivation: Some rural areas also rank poorly due to the challenges of remoteness and lack of infrastructure.\n",
        "\n",
        "Target Areas: The suitability index helps prioritise regions for intervention by integrating the deprivation factors.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "Significance\n",
        "\n",
        "This allows for resources to be allocated to areas with the greatest need. The suitability index helps to answer the research questions by identifying areas for interventions."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "e67_V5XTKAOC"

      "id": "e67_V5XTKAOC"

    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "\n",
        "Results\n",
        "\n",
        "The suitability index for the poorest regions focuses on areas with the highest levels of deprivation across income, education, and employment. These regions are the most suitable areas for intervention."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "cixqGphlC0Nl"
      },
      "id": "cixqGphlC0Nl"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "efb2cf9d-1f67-46a7-a3c7-553d0ce644a9",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "efb2cf9d-1f67-46a7-a3c7-553d0ce644a9"
      },
      "source": [
        "## Discussion\n",
        "\n",
        "The research aimed to answer the questions, what areas in Scotland are the most deprived. And what are possible solutions for this? By using spatial and statistical analysis, the findings provided insights into socio-economic deprivation and highlighted areas suitable for intervention. The analysis showed socio-economic deprivation, both within urban areas and within rural areas. Areas such as Carntyne West and Haghill in Glasgow were identified as highly deprived across education, employment, and income domains. These findings highlight the deprivation in urban settings, where systemic issues such as lack of access to quality education and stable employment exacerbate income inequalities. The Highlands and Islands exhibit socio-economic deprivation, possibly due to seasonal tourism-based work and limited access to services.\n",
        "Limitations\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "The equal weighting of criteria in the MCE doesn’t fully reflect the relative importance of different deprivation domains in daily life. The analysis does not account for temporal changes in deprivation patterns, which could provide additional insights into long-term trends. The data is standardised across zones, so extremes of either end could be being masked. The research is only looking at data and statistics and not real-life implications and case studies, meaning it is not taking into account the people the data represents. Future research could address these limitations by incorporating historical data analysis and using different weights for the MCE. Additionally, qualitative data could be gathered on the people the data is discussing.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "The findings align with existing studies on socio-economic inequalities in Scotland. For example, as Iannelli (2011) discusses, educational attainment directly impacts job opportunities; despite this, socio-economic deprivation reduces access to quality education and therefore higher education. Children from deprived backgrounds face systemic barriers to reaching higher education, such as schools with not enough resources, not enough teachers, having to work part-time, and often less-than-ideal home lives while studying, helping to keep the cycle of poverty going. Despite educational expansion in Scotland that has benefitted people of various classes, inequalities persist. For instance, middle-class children are more likely to secure upper-secondary qualifications and attend prestigious institutions, thus gaining an advantage in job markets that value institutional prestige. This is reflected in the Scottish labour markets as discussed by Iannelli (2011). Scotland’s labour market is at the heart of social class structures that hinder equitable access to high-level employment. Middle-class dominance in professional and managerial roles is maintained through self-recruitment practices and exclusive networks, leaving working-class individuals at a structural disadvantage. Despite this, upward mobility has increased, but these systemic barriers remain significant obstacles (Iannelli, 2011). Regeneration efforts, such as Social Inclusion Partnerships (SIPs), have struggled to address employment disparities effectively. These programmes often prioritise physical infrastructure over socio-economic development, yielding limited outcomes. Competitive funding structures and inadequate community participation have further curtailed the initiatives’ ability to reduce disparities sustainably (Robertson, 2014). Labour market shifts exacerbate inequalities, with precarious work, such as zero-hour contracts, disproportionately affecting less-educated populations. The rise of non-traditional employment compounds economic insecurity and limits opportunities for upward mobility, particularly for disadvantaged groups (Iannelli, 2011).\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "The Scottish education system is a paradox. While access to higher education has seen increased participation, socio-economic inequalities are still deeply ingrained in the education system. Children from disadvantaged families attend under-resourced and understaffed schools, limiting their academic prospects and thus employment prospects. (Iannelli, 2011)\n",
        "\n",
        "Disparities within higher education further these inequalities. Working-class students often attend less prestigious institutions, diminishing their competitiveness in labour markets that favour elite credentials (Robertson, 2014). And even if they attend prestigious institutions, they often have to work while studying, which reduces their ability to study as much as their peers.\n",
        "\n",
        "Addressing these disparities requires targeted interventions to enhance educational quality for disadvantaged students and challenge systemic inequalities within the education system.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "Decades of regeneration programmes in Scotland have demonstrated limited success in tackling poverty due to several persistent challenges: Programmes prioritise housing and infrastructure, neglecting socio-economic determinants of poverty such as education and employment (Robertson, 2014). While housing and infrastructure are crucial, without helping people to study or work, they cannot improve their financial status and then cannot afford housing, and thus the cycle of poverty and reliance on government social benefits begins. Another issue is inadequate monitoring of projects, which hinders the evaluation of projects effectiveness (Robertson, 2014). This means that projects are replicated across the country even if they are not effective. Another issue is that regeneration initiatives often ignore community opinions, limiting their potential (Robertson, 2014); if the community is annoyed or feels neglected by the project, they will not participate. Thus, effective poverty reduction interventions must integrate physical, social, and economic demands while ensuring communities are involved in the project.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "A way in which this could be done is through community-based interventions for addressing poverty. A successful example of this is the Dudley Street Neighbourhood Initiative (DSNI), which emphasises resident-led governance, comprehensive support systems, and sustainable development strategies (Sandel et al., 2016). By using community-based interventions, it allows for projects to be tailored to the residents of an area. For example, some areas could benefit from initiatives like community kitchens and gardens to combat food insecurity, whereas another community could benefit from public transportation support and skills accreditation for unemployed people. Another community could benefit from having community loan funds and job training programs tailored to the local job market. (Torjman, 1998)\n",
        "\n",
        "At the heart of community-based interventions is creating an environment that encourages equal resource distribution, cross-sector collaboration, and monitoring the programme to make sure it is suitable for the community at that time."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "baa93ed6-f26b-483c-9033-dba559fb3040",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "baa93ed6-f26b-483c-9033-dba559fb3040"
      },
      "source": [
        "## Conclusion\n",
        "In conclusion, the research highlights the need for community-based interventions to address socio-economic deprivation in Scotland. Areas like Carntyne West and Haghill in Glasgow and parts of the Highlands and Islands are areas that need different community-based interventions, such as comunity-led initiatives like community kitchens, job training programs, and improved local transportation tailored to meet the community's needs at that time to ensure that projects meet local needs. By prioritising community involvement and collaboration, the Scottish government and local councils can create more effective strategies to reduce socio-economic deprivation.\n",
        "\n"
      ]
    },
